
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dpkg` baraye modiriat bastahaye Debian (*.deb) estefade mishavad. Ba an shoma mitavanid barname-ha ra nasb, hazf va etela'at ra darbare anha be dast avarid.  

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `dpkg -i <baste.deb>` --> 📦 Nasb yek baste az file .deb  
    🔹 `dpkg -r <name-baste>` --> 🗑️ Hazf yek baste (ama file-haye config nemimanad)  
    🔹 `dpkg -P <name-baste>` --> 🧹 Hazf yek baste va hameye file-haye config an  
    🔹 `dpkg -l <name-baste>` --> 🔍 List kardan etela'at darbare yek baste nasb shode  
    🔹 `dpkg -L <name-baste>` --> 📂 List kardan hameye file-ha ke yek baste nasb karde  

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**
    
    $ dpkg -i google-chrome.deb
    
    🔹 Nasb baste google-chrome az file .deb
    
    $ dpkg -r google-chrome-stable
    
    🔹 Hazf baste google-chrome (ama config file-ha mimanad)

✅ **Mesal sade:**
    
    $ dpkg -l | grep chrome
    
    🔹 List kardan hameye baste-ha ke "chrome" dar name anha hast va namayesh anha.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dpkg` command is used to manage Debian packages (*.deb).  It allows you to install, remove, and obtain information about software packages.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `dpkg -i <package.deb>` --> 📦 Install a package from a .deb file
    🔹 `dpkg -r <package-name>` --> 🗑️ Remove a package (but configuration files remain)
    🔹 `dpkg -P <package-name>` --> 🧹 Purge a package and all its configuration files
    🔹 `dpkg -l <package-name>` --> 🔍 List information about an installed package
    🔹 `dpkg -L <package-name>` --> 📂 List all files installed by a package

🛠 **Examples:**
    
    $ dpkg -i google-chrome.deb
    
    🔹 Install the google-chrome package from the .deb file
    
    $ dpkg -r google-chrome-stable
    
    🔹 Remove the google-chrome package (but keeps config files)

✅ **Simple Example:**
    
    $ dpkg -l | grep chrome
    
    🔹 List all packages that have "chrome" in their name and display them.
